## 6. LMS

The LMS is a VBS module (`dashboard/lms.py`, `dashboard/lms_db.py`) surfaced through the Dashboard's
LMS tabs (Courses, Review, Enrollments, Credentials, Escalations). Architecture/schema:
`docs/LMS_QMS_ARCHITECTURE.md`; scope/decisions: `docs/LMS_SCOPE.md`.

### 6.1 Seed the catalog (idempotent)

```bash
docker exec ttis-dashboard python scripts/seed_lms_catalog.py            # seed if empty
docker exec ttis-dashboard python scripts/seed_lms_catalog.py --force    # re-apply (conflict-tolerant)
docker exec ttis-dashboard python scripts/seed_lms_catalog.py --print    # emit dialect SQL (pipe to psql)
```

Seeds courses, rubrics, certifications, curricula, the role→cert matrix, and registered competencies.
Dialect‑portable (SQLite `INSERT OR IGNORE` / Postgres `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING`). `deploy_prod.sh`
runs this automatically.

### 6.2 Policy‑acknowledgment course (R‑ACK‑01/02)

```bash
docker exec ttis-dashboard python scripts/seed_policy_ack.py
```

Creates the `POL-ACK` course: a module + attestation quiz per company policy letter, plus a
**comprehension read‑gate** for policies that have a question bank
(`scripts/policy_lessons/comprehension_banks.json`): **5 random questions, 80% to pass**; on fail the
learner re‑reads and gets a different 5; **3 failures lock the quiz and escalate to a supervisor**.
Earns `CERT-POLACK` (365‑day). Idempotent (skips if `POL-ACK` exists).

**Supervisor escalation / reset:**
- List open escalations: `GET /api/v1/lms/quiz-escalations?status=open` (also the **Escalations** tab).
- Reset a locked learner: `POST /api/v1/lms/enrollments/{enrollment_id}/quizzes/{quiz_id}/reset-lock`.

### 6.3 Verify the LMS is live

- After deploy/seed: the Dashboard **Courses** tab lists courses; the **Review** tab is present; a
  learner can open `POL-ACK`. If Courses is empty → run the catalog seed (§6.1). If the UI looks old →
  confirm the frontend image was pulled and hard‑refresh.

### 6.4 Corpus for the LMS

LMS authoring content is grounded in the same RAG corpus (the `policies` + `corp_confidential`
collections) — see **§7**. The LMS authoring agent (P4b) drafts lessons grounded in the **approved**
corpus and stages them through a three‑stage gate (competent reviewer → CEO release); it is unblocked
once the policy `.docx` set is signed and ingested. Authoring guidance:
`docs/templates/CORPUS_AUTHORING_GUIDE.md`; coverage: `docs/LMS_CORPUS_COVERAGE_CHECKLIST.md`.

---

## 7. Corpus & RAG Ingestion (VBS + LMS)

The RAG corpus grounds agent answers, LYNNE, and LMS authoring. Storage is **ChromaDB** (port 8002,
`data/chroma_db/`) with **hybrid retrieval** (vector embeddings `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` + BM25, fused by
reciprocal‑rank). Query layer: `dashboard/rag.py` (access is enforced server‑side by ABAC capability).

### 7.1 Collections

| Collection | Source | Visibility |
|---|---|---|
| `far_dfars` | FAR/DFARS DITA‑HTML (`H:/Projects/Library/FARHTML`, `DFARSHTML`) | all (name‑scrubbed) |
| `sdvosb_regs` | 13 CFR Part 128 PDF (`H:/Projects/Library/…`) | all (name‑scrubbed) |
| `policies` | `data/documents/policies/**/*.docx` (+ allow‑listed `.xlsx`) | all (name‑scrubbed) |
| `corp_confidential` | `data/documents/corp_confidential/**` | CEO‑only (not scrubbed) |

### 7.2 Where corpus files go

```
ttis-ai/data/documents/
  policies/                 → policies collection (TTIS policy .docx, curriculum subfolders)
    Compliance/ Quality/ Safety/ Technical/ Travel/ curriculum/…
  corp_confidential/        → corp_confidential collection (CEO-only, not scrubbed)
```

Authoring a TTIS interpretive `.docx`: structure per `docs/templates/CORPUS_AUTHORING_GUIDE.md`
(Policy Number header, numbered Heading‑1 sections). **Do not** paste verbatim OSHA/TIA/NEC/BICSI
text (copyright wall) — those are external/attested credentials.

### 7.3 Ingest (idempotent)

The canonical run (throwaway container writing to the shared `ttis-chromadb`):

```bash
docker compose run --rm --no-deps \
  -e CHROMA_HOST=ttis-chromadb -e CHROMA_PORT=8000 \
  -v "H:/Projects/Library:/library:ro" \
  -v "H:/Projects/TTI-S_VBS/ttis-ai/data/documents:/app/data/documents:ro" \
  -v "H:/Projects/TTI-S_VBS/ttis-ai/tools:/app/tools:ro" \
  -v "H:/Projects/TTI-S_VBS/ttis-ai/dashboard:/app/dashboard:ro" \
  -v "H:/Projects/TTI-S_VBS/ttis-ai/scripts:/app/scripts:ro" \
  dashboard python scripts/ingest_rag_corpus.py
```

(Local non‑Docker equivalent: `python main.py --ingest-docs`.) Output logs per collection, e.g.
`policies  120 sections → 980 chunks ingested` and a final total across collections.

**Idempotent / re‑ingest:** chunk IDs are deterministic (`source_ref#chunk`), so re‑running upserts
in place — changed text gets new embeddings, unchanged chunks are silent overwrites. To update: edit
the source doc, re‑run the same command. (Deleted docs leave orphan chunks until cleaned via the
ChromaDB API.) FAR and DFARS share `far_dfars`, so always ingest in one pass.

Custom paths via env: `RAG_LIBRARY_DIR` (default `/library`), `RAG_DOCS_DIR` (default
`/app/data/documents`), `CHROMA_HOST`/`CHROMA_PORT`.

### 7.4 Ingest on prod (background) + the mandatory rebuild

On the VM the corpus library is **inside the container** at `/app/data/documents/library`. Run the
ingest detached (it's long‑running) and watch the log:

```bash
# Start the full ingest in the background
nohup docker exec -e RAG_LIBRARY_DIR=/app/data/documents/library ttis-dashboard \
  python scripts/ingest_rag_corpus.py > ~/ingest.log 2>&1 &

tail -f ~/ingest.log                     # watch progress (Ctrl-C to stop watching)
tail -n 15 ~/ingest.log                  # last lines
pgrep -af ingest_rag_corpus | grep -v grep || echo "ingest finished"
```

Ingest a **single collection** (e.g. re‑load the SDVOSB CFR PDF) without a full run:

```bash
docker exec ttis-dashboard python -c "from tools.rag_ingest import load_cfr_pdf; from dashboard.rag import chunk_sections, ingest_chunks; s=list(load_cfr_pdf('/app/data/documents/library/13 CFR Part 125.pdf','13 CFR Part 125')); print('sdvosb_regs:', ingest_chunks('sdvosb_regs', chunk_sections(s,'sdvosb_regs')), 'chunks')"
```

### 7.5 Rebuild the dashboard after EVERY ingest

Ingest writes to ChromaDB, but the running dashboard caches its retrievers and won't serve the new
corpus until rebuilt:

```bash
cd ~/ttis-ai && git pull --ff-only origin main
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d --build dashboard
```

### 7.6 Verify

After ingest **and** the rebuild, run a RAG search from the Dashboard **Knowledge** tab (or the
LYNNE/agent path) and confirm citations resolve to the new sections.

---

## 8. Ask‑LYNNE

LYNNE is the CEO‑facing conversational EAA (Claude Opus), with grounded RAG citations, tool use, and
propose→confirm workflow initiation. Code: `dashboard/lynne_stream.py` (orchestrator),
`dashboard/lynne_tools.py`, `dashboard/lynne_actions.py`, `dashboard/lynne_projects.py`.

### 8.1 Access

- **Dashboard:** the **Ask‑LYNNE** tab (streaming chat + citations).
- **SSE endpoint:** `POST /api/v1/lynne/stream` (events: `start`, `citations`, `token…`, `done`).
- **Telegram:** the LYNNE bot (same backend via the webhook receiver).

### 8.2 Configuration (env)

| Variable | Default | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `LYNNE_ALLOWED_PRINCIPALS` | unset | Allow‑list of principals (opt‑in restriction). |
| `LYNNE_WEB_SEARCH` | `1` | Live web search tool. |
| `LYNNE_PROJECTS` | `1` | GRID executive‑project tools. |
| `LYNNE_MEMORY` | `1` | Rich cross‑turn memory (recall earlier research/docs). |
| `LYNNE_OUTPUT_FORMAT` / `LYNNE_OUTPUT_EMAIL` | `gdoc` / unset | Save‑to‑Drive format / email recipient. |
| `GOOGLE_DRIVE_LYNNE_FOLDER` / `GOOGLE_DRIVE_SHARED_ID` | unset | Drive target for saved runs. |
| Durable runs | — | `LYNNE_STEP_GATES`, `LYNNE_STEP_GATE_TIMEOUT`, `LYNNE_RUN_TTL_SECONDS`, `LYNNE_SEQ_COMPACTION`, `LYNNE_SEQ_COMPACT_TOKENS`, `LYNNE_DIGEST_MODEL`. |
| Tool keys | unset | `GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY` (maps/places), `TICKETMASTER_API_KEY` (events), `DUFFEL_API_TOKEN` (travel). Tool appears only if its key is set; weather (Weather.gov) needs none. |

### 8.3 Google Workspace (Gmail/Calendar/Drive) for LYNNE

```bash
python scripts/setup_google_workspace.py     # interactive: GCP project, enable APIs, service account,
                                             # domain-wide delegation, env vars, Docker mount
```

It configures a service account + domain‑wide delegation and prints the env vars to add
(`GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON`, `GOOGLE_IMPERSONATED_USER`, Drive folder IDs). Mount `./secrets`
read‑only into the container. Verify:

```bash
docker exec ttis-dashboard python -c "from tools.google_gmail import GoogleGmail; print(len(GoogleGmail().list_emails(max_results=3)))"
```

### 8.4 Capabilities

- **Read tools (inline):** weather, directions/places (Maps), travel search (Duffel), Drive/Gmail/Calendar read, web search.
- **Propose→confirm:** initiate workflow, sync deadlines to calendar, delegate research.
- **Direct (audit‑logged):** GRID project create/update/delete, calendar event cleanup.
- **Playbooks:** savable templated multi‑step tasks (Ask‑LYNNE + Telegram).
- **Durable runs:** Redis‑buffered, survive disconnect, optional save‑to‑Drive; mid‑run confirm gates.
- **Integrity guardrails** (`agents/integrity_policy.py`): anti‑assumption (no unsourced identity/authority
  claims), confidence scoring, `needs_review` flag below threshold.

### 8.5 Troubleshoot

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| "Save to Drive" fails | Workspace not configured | Re‑run `setup_google_workspace.py`; check `GOOGLE_*` env + Drive folder ID. |
| A tool isn't offered | its API key is unset | Set `GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY` / `DUFFEL_API_TOKEN` / etc.; restart. |
| Web search missing | `LYNNE_WEB_SEARCH=0` | Set `=1`, restart. |
| Streaming arrives in bursts | Caddy buffering | Ensure `flush_interval -1` on the dashboard proxy in `config/Caddyfile`. |
| 429 rate‑limit | Anthropic tier/limit | LYNNE auto‑retries with back‑off; raise the org token‑per‑minute limit if persistent. |

---

## 9. Pursuite (GovCon capture/proposal platform)

Separate product at `H:\Projects\Pursuite\app` — an npm‑workspaces monorepo (`apps/api`, `apps/web`;
internally codenamed **BidCommandPro**). It feeds the TTIS VBS through the **Pursuite webhook** (CRM
events → port 8001). Local dev runs in Docker; config is injected via `env_file: .env` (see the
**Docker Desktop / WSL2 `.env` gotcha** in §1.4). Prod images are tagged `pursuite/api:YYYYMMDD`. The
admin/troubleshooting CLI lives in `apps/api/src/db/scripts/` and **all helper scripts run from
`apps/api/`** (they read the monorepo‑root `.env` automatically). **When in doubt, run
`npm run check-health` first** (§9.7).

> Two sibling dirs, easy to confuse: `src/db/seeds/` = **seeding** scripts (run once to populate a
> demo/dev env); `src/db/scripts/` = **admin CLI** tools (run on‑demand to inspect/modify existing data).

### 9.1 Local run & container control (Docker)

```powershell
cd H:\Projects\Pursuite\app
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.localtest.yml up -d --force-recreate
docker compose ps

# Per-container control
docker compose up -d --force-recreate web    # recreate the web container
docker compose restart api                    # restart the API
docker compose logs api -f                     # follow API logs
docker compose logs api --tail=5               # confirm API status
```

> Always **recreate** rather than restart (`… up -d --force-recreate`, or `down --remove-orphans` then
> `up`). Restarting a stale container replays the old single‑file `.env` mount and fails — see §1.4.

**Log in via the web UI (local-auth):** there is no separate username field. Set **Organization**
to `default`, click **"Admin only? Use local login"**, then enter the admin **email** and local-admin
password. On a clean standalone install Pursuite Manager auto-creates `admin@pursuite.local` in org
`default` and writes the first-run password to `%APPDATA%\Pursuite\first-run-admin.txt`. Use that
first-run password once, then create a named admin account and rotate/clear the temporary local password
(see section 9.9).

**Running CLI scripts against local infra** needs the DB + Redis env present in the shell:

```powershell
$env:DATABASE_URL = 'postgresql://bidcommand:devpassword@localhost:5432/bidcommand'   # local dev only
$env:REDIS_URL    = 'redis://localhost:6379'
```

### 9.2 Seed TTI‑Solutions' own tenant (telecom bootstrap + market intel)

The seed scripts live in the `apps/api` workspace, so run them from there (or add `-w apps/api` from
the monorepo root):

```powershell
cd H:\Projects\Pursuite\app\apps\api

# 1) Bootstrap company data — NAICS 238210 (wiring), 517919 (telecom), 561621 (security systems)
npm run seed:tti -- --org tti-solutions --email charles@tti-solutions.com --password "YourPW" `
  --naics 238210,517919,561621 --opportunities 6

# 2) Pull real market intelligence from USASpending.gov for that org
npm run seed:enrich -- --org tti-solutions

# 3) Refresh market data periodically
npm run seed:enrich -- --org tti-solutions --reset
```

Direct equivalent: `npx tsx src/db/seeds/telecom-bootstrap.ts --org tti-solutions …`.

### 9.3 Demo seeds (sales / AI‑positioning demos)

```powershell
cd H:\Projects\Pursuite\app\apps\api

# Simplest — named org with a local-auth login
npm run seed:ai-demo -- --org demo-ai --email admin@example.com --password "Demo@2026!" --naics 541512

# Reset an existing named org (purge + re-seed)
npm run seed:ai-demo -- --org demo-ai --reset --email admin@example.com --password "Demo@2026!"

# No flags = auto-generated unique slug, default email, no local-auth password
npm run seed:ai-demo
```

Flags: `--org <slug>` (named; omit → auto unique slug), `--email`/`--password` (local‑auth login; omit
→ none), `--reset` (purge the named `--org` then re‑seed; omitting `--org` always creates fresh),
`--naics <csv>`. Direct: `npx tsx src/db/seeds/ai-positioning-demo.ts …`.

**What the AI demo builds** — a 3‑bid / 2‑agency story arc that exercises the three AI initiatives:
CISA CDM Phase 4 (**LOSS** to Booz Allen, with a written debrief) → Army DEVCOM MCADE (**WIN** $12.8M,
banked win themes) → CISA ZTA Advisory (**ACTIVE**, due in 28 days, the test bed) → NIH IT
Modernization (**QUALIFYING**). It demonstrates (1) **Capture‑Context Injection** (win themes,
debriefs, CRM hot buttons, bid/no‑bid rationale, compliance scan, content library), (2) **Agentic
Content Research** (real agency DHS CISA + real NAICS 541512 → live USASpending.gov awarded‑contract
queries), and (3) **Section‑Type Intelligent Pipelines** (six section types, each with type‑specific
context; Price/Cost links to the CPQ quote). Using a real agency + NAICS is what makes USASpending
return actual awards in the demo.

**Generic CRM test data** (separate from the tenant/demo seeds — bulk accounts + contacts for load/UX
testing). Two scripts in `G:\BidCommandPro\seed\`: run `generate.js` first (→ `accounts.csv` 100 rows
+ `contacts.csv` ~1,615 rows; 10 "anchor" accounts get a 5‑level org chart), then `seed.js` to POST
them to a running API:

```powershell
node generate.js
node seed.js --url http://localhost:3001 --token <jwt>   # --dry to preview, --delay 50 to throttle
```

`--token` is a JWT from `POST /api/v1/auth/login`. `seed.js` imports in dependency order (accounts →
contacts → wire `reportsTo` hierarchy) with a live progress bar.

